1
00:00:00,835 --> 00:00:02,628
It's H-A-W-T--

2
00:00:02,628 --> 00:00:04,588
Guys, what happened?

3
00:00:04,588 --> 00:00:07,800
Apparently, they found him
unconscious on a park bench.

4
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:09,760
Oh, my God, is he okay?

5
00:00:09,760 --> 00:00:11,637
We don't know,
we just got here.

6
00:00:11,637 --> 00:00:15,850
NURSE:
He's ready for visitors now.
He's in 1023.

7
00:00:17,518 --> 00:00:18,853
Hi.

8
00:00:18,853 --> 00:00:22,230
Oh, welcome, my old friends.
Welcome.

9
00:00:22,230 --> 00:00:25,526
Pierce, what happened?
We were all so worried.

10
00:00:25,526 --> 00:00:27,778
It was the pills.
They just took me over.

11
00:00:27,778 --> 00:00:30,781
I saw awful,
horrible things.

12
00:00:30,781 --> 00:00:33,200
<i>Demons, Aliens, Critters 3,</i>

13
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:35,619
something called
Bruce Willis'<i> Surrogates.</i>

14
00:00:35,619 --> 00:00:37,454
PIERCE:
Oh.

15
00:00:37,454 --> 00:00:38,706
Abed, what are guys doing?

16
00:00:38,706 --> 00:00:40,541
ABED:
It's okay, just act natural.

17
00:00:40,541 --> 00:00:42,459
<i>Pierce asked me</i>
<i>to document his life</i>

18
00:00:42,459 --> 00:00:43,919
<i>for historical purposes.</i>

19
00:00:43,919 --> 00:00:45,253
At first, I said no.

20
00:00:45,253 --> 00:00:47,339
At the risk of sounding
overly sensitive,

21
00:00:47,339 --> 00:00:49,466
I feel bored by Pierce
as a subject.

22
00:00:49,466 --> 00:00:51,301
But I'm excited
about the narrative

23
00:00:51,301 --> 00:00:54,054
of the documentary format.
It's easier to tell a story

24
00:00:54,054 --> 00:00:56,348
when you can cut to people
explaining things.

25
00:00:56,348 --> 00:00:58,141
PIERCE:
I've called everyone here

26
00:00:58,141 --> 00:01:00,019
so that I could put my house
in order,

27
00:01:00,019 --> 00:01:02,563
bequeath parting gifts,

28
00:01:02,563 --> 00:01:04,690
say my final words
to each of you.

29
00:01:04,690 --> 00:01:07,401
Final words?
You're gonna kill us?

30
00:01:07,401 --> 00:01:11,112
No, dummy,
the pills wiped me out.

31
00:01:11,112 --> 00:01:12,406
I'm dying.

32
00:01:12,406 --> 00:01:15,075
[ANNIE &amp; SHIRLEY WHIMPER]

33
00:01:15,075 --> 00:01:17,912
I'm not really dying.
Over the last few weeks,

34
00:01:17,912 --> 00:01:20,080
it's become apparent
how little respect

35
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:22,082
this group has for me.

36
00:01:22,082 --> 00:01:26,127
So I summoned them here
to exact my revenge.

37
00:01:26,127 --> 00:01:28,672
See? Fish in a barrel.

38
00:01:28,672 --> 00:01:30,549
[THE 88'S "AT LEAST
IT WAS HERE" PLAYING]

39
00:01:30,549 --> 00:01:32,300
♪<i> Give me some rope</i>
<i>Tie me to dream</i> ♪

40
00:01:32,300 --> 00:01:35,554
♪<i> Give me the hope</i>
<i>To run out of steam</i> ♪

41
00:01:35,554 --> 00:01:38,891
♪<i> Somebody said</i>
<i>It could be here</i> ♪

42
00:01:38,891 --> 00:01:42,978
♪<i> We could be roped up</i>
<i>Tied up, dead in a year</i> ♪

43
00:01:42,978 --> 00:01:47,942
♪<i> I can't count the reasons</i>
<i>I should stay</i> ♪

44
00:01:47,942 --> 00:01:53,530
♪<i> One by one</i>
<i>They all just fade away</i> ♪

45
00:01:56,075 --> 00:01:57,826
I'm so sad,
I don't know what to do.

46
00:01:57,826 --> 00:02:00,287
Usually if I need to cheer up,
I make fun of Pierce,

47
00:02:00,287 --> 00:02:02,831
but now
it'd just make me sadder.

48
00:02:02,831 --> 00:02:04,959
It's Gregory Hines
all over again.

49
00:02:04,959 --> 00:02:06,752
JEFF:
I'm sure he'll be fine.

50
00:02:06,752 --> 00:02:08,503
You know how dramatic
Pierce gets.

51
00:02:08,503 --> 00:02:10,130
Remember when
he had the hiccups

52
00:02:10,130 --> 00:02:12,049
and pulled the fire alarm?
Just relax.

53
00:02:12,049 --> 00:02:13,634
He's here
because we relaxed.

54
00:02:13,634 --> 00:02:15,343
No, he's here
because he relaxed.

55
00:02:15,343 --> 00:02:17,429
A handful of pills
at a time.

56
00:02:17,429 --> 00:02:19,974
That's all over now,
we're here for him.

57
00:02:19,974 --> 00:02:21,767
So there's no point
in feeling bad.

58
00:02:21,767 --> 00:02:24,728
We know there's no point,
we just felt like feeling it.

59
00:02:24,728 --> 00:02:26,730
Yeah, Jeff,
what are you, Abed?

60
00:02:26,730 --> 00:02:28,440
Oh, sorry, Abed.
ABED: No problem.

61
00:02:28,440 --> 00:02:30,692
Doesn't bother me.
Mr. Hawthorne is ready

62
00:02:30,692 --> 00:02:33,112
to commence his bequeathings.
[TROY GIGGLING]

63
00:02:33,112 --> 00:02:35,739
Shouldn't you be telling
that to an orderly?

64
00:02:35,739 --> 00:02:36,991
He's gonna give us gifts.

65
00:02:36,991 --> 00:02:38,993
Oh, cool.

66
00:02:38,993 --> 00:02:41,369
I mean...

67
00:02:41,369 --> 00:02:42,704
Cool.

68
00:02:42,704 --> 00:02:44,331
I don't want Pierce to die,

69
00:02:44,331 --> 00:02:47,001
but if I'm gonna get
bequeathed upon,

70
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:49,711
I'd liked to be bequeathed
a drum kit

71
00:02:49,711 --> 00:02:51,755
or a signed photo
of actor LeVar Burton.

72
00:02:51,755 --> 00:02:54,257
<i>Those would be</i>
<i>my top two wishes.</i>

73
00:02:54,257 --> 00:02:56,802
My third wish would be
a million wishes.

74
00:02:56,802 --> 00:02:58,345
But I'd just use them all

75
00:02:58,345 --> 00:03:01,056
on a million signed photos
of actor LeVar Burton.

76
00:03:01,056 --> 00:03:04,601
Hello, Pierce.
NURSE: Hey.

77
00:03:04,601 --> 00:03:06,895
Hi. I got you some things
from the gift shop

78
00:03:06,895 --> 00:03:08,271
to cheer you up.

79
00:03:08,271 --> 00:03:09,690
I got you
a John Grisham novel

80
00:03:09,690 --> 00:03:11,274
and a funny
little coffee mug.

81
00:03:11,274 --> 00:03:13,694
See how the flea's doormat
says "Dog Sweet Dog"?

82
00:03:13,694 --> 00:03:15,278
PIERCE:
Shirley, we both know

83
00:03:15,278 --> 00:03:17,572
that you and I are the most
hated in the group.

84
00:03:17,572 --> 00:03:20,034
We do?
And since in my absence,

85
00:03:20,034 --> 00:03:22,077
you'll be
the new blacksheep or--

86
00:03:22,077 --> 00:03:25,164
I'm sorry, that's offensive.
Black swan.

87
00:03:25,164 --> 00:03:27,082
I want you to have this.

88
00:03:27,082 --> 00:03:31,003
It's a compact record,
and it contains an audio file

89
00:03:31,003 --> 00:03:32,754
of your group
talking about you

90
00:03:32,754 --> 00:03:34,297
while you're
out of the room.

91
00:03:34,297 --> 00:03:36,675
It's all here,
burnt into this diskette

92
00:03:36,675 --> 00:03:38,259
by optical lasers.

93
00:03:38,259 --> 00:03:41,262
I don't believe you.
It sounds like science fiction--

94
00:03:41,262 --> 00:03:43,640
No, I don't believe
there's anything on that.

95
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:46,768
Then I guess
this is goodbye forever.

96
00:03:46,768 --> 00:03:49,771
Goodbye, Pierce.

97
00:03:55,110 --> 00:03:56,486
Smell you later.

98
00:03:56,486 --> 00:03:57,779
He said it's a recording

99
00:03:57,779 --> 00:03:59,406
of you all
talking behind my back.

100
00:03:59,406 --> 00:04:01,616
That's ridiculous.
That's what I told him

101
00:04:01,616 --> 00:04:04,828
because you all don't do that,
right?

102
00:04:04,828 --> 00:04:07,164
[INDISTINCT ANNOUNCEMENT
OVER PA]

103
00:04:09,583 --> 00:04:12,711
Mr. Hawthorne is requesting
Sour Face.

104
00:04:13,545 --> 00:04:15,923
[SIGHS]

105
00:04:15,923 --> 00:04:17,591
Knock, knock.

106
00:04:17,591 --> 00:04:19,593
Is that you, death?
It's Britta.

107
00:04:19,593 --> 00:04:21,929
Oh.
I just wanna tell you

108
00:04:21,929 --> 00:04:23,972
that you don't have
to give me anything.

109
00:04:23,972 --> 00:04:26,058
I'm happy
to spend time with you.

110
00:04:26,058 --> 00:04:28,102
Know what Dylan Thomas
said about death?

111
00:04:28,102 --> 00:04:31,146
No, tell me.
Okay, bluff called.

112
00:04:31,146 --> 00:04:33,398
You're the selfless one
in the group, right?

113
00:04:33,398 --> 00:04:35,483
Haven't thought about myself
in years.

114
00:04:35,483 --> 00:04:37,694
That's what makes you
the perfect recipient

115
00:04:37,694 --> 00:04:40,781
of this bequeathment.
It's a check for $10,000

116
00:04:40,781 --> 00:04:42,365
with the payee line blank.

117
00:04:42,365 --> 00:04:45,035
So that you can give it
to the charity of your choice.

118
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:51,374
Wow.
Pierce, this is surprising.

119
00:04:51,374 --> 00:04:52,834
After what you gave Shirley,

120
00:04:52,834 --> 00:04:56,004
we thought you were playing
mind games. Thank you.

121
00:04:58,799 --> 00:05:00,634
If you're so inclined,

122
00:05:00,634 --> 00:05:03,344
you could always write
your own name in there.

123
00:05:06,431 --> 00:05:07,766
Toodles.

124
00:05:07,766 --> 00:05:09,684
I don't wanna die
in a place like this.

125
00:05:09,684 --> 00:05:11,394
People shouldn't die
in the place

126
00:05:11,394 --> 00:05:12,687
<i>People</i> magazines do.

127
00:05:12,687 --> 00:05:14,522
I hope to die
surrounded by my family.

128
00:05:14,522 --> 00:05:16,233
Only way I'd agree to be
by family.

129
00:05:16,233 --> 00:05:18,401
Me and Abed have an agreement.
One dies,

130
00:05:18,401 --> 00:05:19,945
stage it
to look like a suicide

131
00:05:19,945 --> 00:05:21,947
caused by the cancellation
of<i> Firefly.</i>

132
00:05:21,947 --> 00:05:25,575
We're gonna get that show
back on the air, buddy.

133
00:05:26,409 --> 00:05:29,121
How'd it go?
Huh?

134
00:05:29,121 --> 00:05:31,790
Oh, fine. He gave me
a check for $10,000

135
00:05:31,790 --> 00:05:33,708
to give to the charity
of my choice.

136
00:05:33,708 --> 00:05:36,753
See? He's not messing with us.
Maybe he just hates Shirley.

137
00:05:36,753 --> 00:05:38,463
What?

138
00:05:38,463 --> 00:05:40,007
Yeah, maybe.

139
00:05:40,007 --> 00:05:41,842
<i>I need to research</i>
<i>a few charities</i>

140
00:05:41,842 --> 00:05:43,551
because some take a lot
off the top.

141
00:05:43,551 --> 00:05:46,221
You think you're giving money
to people that need it,

142
00:05:46,221 --> 00:05:48,515
and you're really giving it
to some middle man

143
00:05:48,515 --> 00:05:51,685
who's gonna pay off their
parking tickets, credit cards,

144
00:05:51,685 --> 00:05:54,896
and keep from getting
kicked out of her place in...

145
00:05:54,896 --> 00:05:57,482
April. Hah.

146
00:05:57,482 --> 00:05:59,526
He'd like to see Annie next.

147
00:05:59,526 --> 00:06:00,861
You know what? No.

148
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:02,154
He'll see Jeff next.

149
00:06:02,154 --> 00:06:04,198
NURSE: But you're not--
JEFF: Or what?

150
00:06:04,198 --> 00:06:06,116
You'll do twice
as much work as a doctor

151
00:06:06,116 --> 00:06:07,909
for half the pay?
Thank you?

152
00:06:07,909 --> 00:06:10,745
Called a "complisult."
Part compliment, part insult.

153
00:06:10,745 --> 00:06:13,540
He invented them,
I coined the term.

154
00:06:13,540 --> 00:06:16,793
See what I just did there?
That was an "explanabrag."

155
00:06:17,961 --> 00:06:20,505
Hello, Jeffrey.
Pierce.

156
00:06:22,883 --> 00:06:25,093
I've thought about this day
many times,

157
00:06:25,093 --> 00:06:27,304
but I've always imagined it
differently.

158
00:06:27,304 --> 00:06:29,514
For starters, I thought
you'd be the one in bed

159
00:06:29,514 --> 00:06:32,559
and I'd be a hologram.
What?

160
00:06:32,559 --> 00:06:35,687
Never mind.
There's no time for that now.

161
00:06:38,190 --> 00:06:40,984
Pierce. It's starting to seem

162
00:06:40,984 --> 00:06:43,028
that you're using
the social leverage

163
00:06:43,028 --> 00:06:44,988
afforded you
by your alleged deathbed,

164
00:06:44,988 --> 00:06:47,782
to exact complicated acts
of psychological vengeance

165
00:06:47,782 --> 00:06:50,077
on those closest to you.
Vengeance? Oh, no.

166
00:06:50,077 --> 00:06:52,620
I was never one
to hold a grudge, Jeffrey.

167
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:56,041
My father held grudges.
I'll always hate him for that.

168
00:06:56,041 --> 00:06:57,667
You get along
with your father?

169
00:06:57,667 --> 00:06:58,919
I got along without him.

170
00:06:58,919 --> 00:07:00,587
Oh. That's no good.

171
00:07:00,587 --> 00:07:01,922
You don't want your dad to die

172
00:07:01,922 --> 00:07:03,506
before you tell him
how you feel.

173
00:07:03,506 --> 00:07:05,384
I'm sure.
Let's nip this in the bud.

174
00:07:05,384 --> 00:07:08,345
Pierce, we're sorry we didn't
respond quickly enough

175
00:07:08,345 --> 00:07:09,679
to your pill addiction.

176
00:07:09,679 --> 00:07:13,183
Is there any chance
that apology is enough?

177
00:07:13,183 --> 00:07:16,061
Are you ready
to be bequeathed upon, Jeff?

178
00:07:16,061 --> 00:07:19,314
Yeah. Blow my mind.

179
00:07:19,314 --> 00:07:20,941
I found your father.

180
00:07:22,025 --> 00:07:23,360
Did you now?

181
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:27,030
William Winger,
born Oklahoma City, 1945.

182
00:07:27,030 --> 00:07:29,574
1974,
married Doreen Fitzgerald,

183
00:07:29,574 --> 00:07:31,243
divorced in 1983.

184
00:07:31,243 --> 00:07:33,245
Most recently,
residing in Dorchester.

185
00:07:33,245 --> 00:07:35,956
Currently sitting
in a Town Car

186
00:07:35,956 --> 00:07:38,208
on its way
to this very hospital.

187
00:07:38,208 --> 00:07:40,085
Should be here
in an hour or so.

188
00:07:40,085 --> 00:07:44,423
Give or take a father.
That it?

189
00:07:44,423 --> 00:07:46,507
Yep.
All right,

190
00:07:46,507 --> 00:07:48,343
see you at the funeral.

191
00:07:49,970 --> 00:07:54,015
And so it is bequeathed.

192
00:07:56,601 --> 00:07:58,770
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

193
00:08:01,022 --> 00:08:02,774
What are you gonna say
to your dad?

194
00:08:02,774 --> 00:08:04,484
I'm not gonna say anything.

195
00:08:04,484 --> 00:08:07,446
I won't have to because Pierce
is playing head games with us.

196
00:08:07,446 --> 00:08:09,906
Decided not to listen to it.
What?

197
00:08:09,906 --> 00:08:15,078
I'm not gonna listen to the CD
of you guys talking about me

198
00:08:15,078 --> 00:08:16,496
because I forgive you.

199
00:08:16,496 --> 00:08:18,957
How do we know
what we're being forgiven for?

200
00:08:18,957 --> 00:08:20,875
We don't even know
what's on there.

201
00:08:20,875 --> 00:08:22,710
And you never have to.

202
00:08:22,710 --> 00:08:24,296
Hmm?

203
00:08:26,673 --> 00:08:29,092
What if he is coming?
What are you gonna say to him?

204
00:08:29,092 --> 00:08:31,886
Here.
I'll be him, I'll be him.

205
00:08:33,054 --> 00:08:34,555
Hi, hey.

206
00:08:34,555 --> 00:08:36,433
Hi, I'm Jeff's dad, hi.

207
00:08:36,433 --> 00:08:37,642
Hi, Jeff's dad,

208
00:08:37,642 --> 00:08:40,020
I'm Britta's dad.
What? Why?

209
00:08:40,020 --> 00:08:41,771
Got drunk,
didn't have a condom.

210
00:08:41,771 --> 00:08:44,316
And her mom gets freaky
when she hears Oingo Boingo.

211
00:08:44,316 --> 00:08:47,319
Wish I could relate but, like
my son, I'm a closet homosexual.

212
00:08:47,319 --> 00:08:49,488
Don't apologize.
You're talking to the guy

213
00:08:49,488 --> 00:08:52,407
that banged Britta's mom.
I have no standards.

214
00:08:52,407 --> 00:08:54,159
What do you say
we take a tumble?

215
00:08:54,159 --> 00:08:56,536
You're under arrest,
I'm an undercover cop.

216
00:08:56,536 --> 00:08:58,830
It's not illegal to be gay.
It is here in Iran.

217
00:08:58,830 --> 00:09:00,499
Not when we're
in the Green Zone.

218
00:09:00,499 --> 00:09:02,209
That's Iraq.
Well, what do I know?

219
00:09:02,209 --> 00:09:05,003
I'm Jeff Winger's
dumb gay dad.

220
00:09:06,463 --> 00:09:10,175
My father was a two-bit con man
of so little substance,

221
00:09:10,175 --> 00:09:12,219
he couldn't leave a trail
if he wanted to.

222
00:09:12,219 --> 00:09:14,429
I don't care if Pierce hired
Scotland Yard,

223
00:09:14,429 --> 00:09:17,015
he isn't gonna track him down
from a hospital bed.

224
00:09:17,015 --> 00:09:19,893
Money can't just make
people appear.

225
00:09:19,893 --> 00:09:23,730
Excuse me.
I'm looking for Troy Barnes.

226
00:09:23,730 --> 00:09:26,149
Pierce Hawthorne sent me.

227
00:09:32,030 --> 00:09:33,407
Hey, Troy?

228
00:09:35,242 --> 00:09:36,951
Hi. I'm LeVar Burton.

229
00:09:40,372 --> 00:09:42,874
Pierce got LeVar Burton
to come here for Troy?

230
00:09:42,874 --> 00:09:44,709
Is there anyone
he can't produce?

231
00:09:44,709 --> 00:09:46,753
Now I'm really getting mad.

232
00:09:46,753 --> 00:09:49,381
Why am I the only one
he decided to torture?

233
00:09:49,381 --> 00:09:51,383
[INDISTINCT ANNOUNCEMENT
OVER PA]

234
00:09:56,430 --> 00:09:58,806
I told Pierce
a thousand times

235
00:09:58,806 --> 00:10:02,060
I never wanted to meet LeVar
in person!

236
00:10:02,060 --> 00:10:04,229
I just wanted a picture!

237
00:10:04,229 --> 00:10:07,315
You can't disappoint
a picture!

238
00:10:07,315 --> 00:10:10,569
I hate you, Pierce! Aah-hah!

239
00:10:10,569 --> 00:10:12,487
I hate you so much!

240
00:10:12,487 --> 00:10:13,780
[SCREAMS]

241
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:15,740
[CLEARS THROAT]

242
00:10:18,243 --> 00:10:19,494
Annie, I forgive you.

243
00:10:19,494 --> 00:10:22,330
NURSE:
Annie Edison?

244
00:10:22,330 --> 00:10:24,207
Your bequeathal is at hand.

245
00:10:25,542 --> 00:10:28,044
Do you have a regular job
here?

246
00:10:30,755 --> 00:10:34,134
Annie, I know
you're being strong for me,

247
00:10:34,134 --> 00:10:35,885
I give you permission
to weep.

248
00:10:35,885 --> 00:10:38,388
I'm crying on the inside.

249
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:42,350
Gross. Well, in any case,
I wanna give you this.

250
00:10:42,350 --> 00:10:46,438
It's been in my family
for six generations.

251
00:10:46,438 --> 00:10:48,731
Now it's yours.

252
00:10:48,731 --> 00:10:50,150
Thank you.

253
00:10:55,196 --> 00:10:57,824
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
<i>Wheelchair assist</i>
<i>in Admitting.</i>

254
00:10:57,824 --> 00:11:00,118
<i>Could I please have</i>
<i>a wheelchair assist</i>

255
00:11:00,118 --> 00:11:01,495
<i>in Admitting, please?</i>

256
00:11:01,495 --> 00:11:03,037
[SHIRLEY SIGHS]

257
00:11:03,037 --> 00:11:04,872
Mm-mm.

258
00:11:04,872 --> 00:11:06,249
[CHUCKLES]

259
00:11:07,875 --> 00:11:10,504
ABED: Do you wanna see your dad?
He's not coming.

260
00:11:10,504 --> 00:11:13,089
ABED: But do you wanna see him?
No.

261
00:11:13,089 --> 00:11:15,175
ABED:
Then why aren't you leaving?

262
00:11:15,175 --> 00:11:16,635
Because I don't care

263
00:11:16,635 --> 00:11:18,803
and I'm not gonna let him think
that I care.

264
00:11:18,803 --> 00:11:21,181
ABED: Your dad or Pierce?
There is no dad.

265
00:11:21,181 --> 00:11:22,765
And get this thing
out of my face.

266
00:11:22,765 --> 00:11:24,476
And don't you dare
intercut this

267
00:11:24,476 --> 00:11:26,811
with footage of me
freaking out.

268
00:11:29,606 --> 00:11:31,107
Aah! Ha-ha-ha.

269
00:11:31,107 --> 00:11:33,485
ABED:
Is there footage of you
freaking out?

270
00:11:33,485 --> 00:11:35,945
Abed, I'm gonna kill you

271
00:11:35,945 --> 00:11:37,531
and Pierce and Britta

272
00:11:37,531 --> 00:11:40,992
and anyone else who thinks
I care about any of this.

273
00:11:40,992 --> 00:11:44,371
So do you go to school
nearby?

274
00:11:45,497 --> 00:11:47,915
Well, are you more familiar
with me

275
00:11:47,915 --> 00:11:50,043
from<i> Star Trek</i>
or<i> Reading Rainbow?</i>

276
00:11:50,043 --> 00:11:52,795
<i>Reading Rainbow</i> was the show
I hosted and produced

277
00:11:52,795 --> 00:11:54,422
for 25 years on PBS.

278
00:11:54,422 --> 00:11:56,383
Ever seen it?

279
00:11:56,383 --> 00:11:59,427
♪<i> Butterfly in the sky</i> ♪

280
00:11:59,427 --> 00:12:02,305
♪ I can go twice as high ♪

281
00:12:02,305 --> 00:12:05,099
♪ Take a look
It's in a book ♪

282
00:12:05,099 --> 00:12:08,353
♪<i> Reading Rainbow</i> ♪

283
00:12:08,353 --> 00:12:10,897
♪<i> Reading Rainbow</i> ♪

284
00:12:10,897 --> 00:12:13,149
[SOBBING]

285
00:12:13,149 --> 00:12:16,735
Oh. Set phasers to "love me."

286
00:12:16,735 --> 00:12:18,112
What does it mean?

287
00:12:18,112 --> 00:12:19,656
What do you mean?

288
00:12:19,656 --> 00:12:22,701
No riddles. You're screwing
around with everyone.

289
00:12:22,701 --> 00:12:25,662
You gave me a tiara,
what does it mean?

290
00:12:25,662 --> 00:12:28,665
Are these blood diamonds?

291
00:12:28,665 --> 00:12:31,209
Are they Holocaust diamonds?

292
00:12:31,209 --> 00:12:33,794
No.
Well, what does it mean?

293
00:12:33,794 --> 00:12:36,923
It means you're my favorite.

294
00:12:36,923 --> 00:12:38,757
What does that mean?

295
00:12:38,757 --> 00:12:42,512
BRITTA:
<i>I did it,</i>
<i>I gave away the money.</i>

296
00:12:42,512 --> 00:12:44,472
The Red Cross.

297
00:12:44,472 --> 00:12:47,225
You know what that makes me?
A terrible person

298
00:12:47,225 --> 00:12:49,102
because if that camera
wasn't on me,

299
00:12:49,102 --> 00:12:51,730
I would have taken that money
right out of the mouths

300
00:12:51,730 --> 00:12:55,692
of crippled, starving,
malaria-ridden refugee kids.

301
00:12:55,692 --> 00:12:58,278
And now I know that forever.

302
00:12:58,278 --> 00:13:00,655
Thanks, Pierce.

303
00:13:00,655 --> 00:13:04,701
Britta,
you've got to forgive yourself.

304
00:13:04,701 --> 00:13:07,245
I've forgiven all of you
for the horrible things--

305
00:13:07,245 --> 00:13:10,081
Oh, for crying out loud.
We're gonna listen to it.

306
00:13:10,081 --> 00:13:13,334
I don't wanna listen to it.
Britta, please. Britta.

307
00:13:13,334 --> 00:13:16,170
Britta, wait. Britta.

308
00:13:18,715 --> 00:13:20,883
SHIRLEY [ON RECORDING]:
<i>I'll be right back.</i>

309
00:13:20,883 --> 00:13:22,843
<i>Don't learn anything</i>
<i>without me.</i>

310
00:13:22,843 --> 00:13:25,096
PIERCE:
<i>So how much do we all hate</i>
<i>Shirley?</i>

311
00:13:25,096 --> 00:13:26,847
ANNIE:
<i>Pierce, knock it off.</i>

312
00:13:26,847 --> 00:13:29,476
JEFF:
<i>Hey, James Bond,</i>
<i>stop trying to record us</i>

313
00:13:29,476 --> 00:13:30,769
<i>with that stupid spy pen.</i>

314
00:13:30,769 --> 00:13:32,604
ABED:
<i>We can see the blinking light.</i>

315
00:13:32,604 --> 00:13:35,440
TROY:
<i>Why do you keep trying</i>
<i>to record us bad-mouthing?</i>

316
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:37,816
JEFF:
<i>He thinks friendship</i>
<i>is a competition,</i>

317
00:13:37,816 --> 00:13:39,653
<i>he's trying</i>
<i>to get the upper hand.</i>

318
00:13:39,653 --> 00:13:41,946
PIERCE:
<i>You think Shirley's</i>
<i>any different?</i>

319
00:13:41,946 --> 00:13:43,531
GROUP:<i> Yes.</i> 
JEFF:<i> Moron.</i>

320
00:13:43,531 --> 00:13:45,784
SHIRLEY:<i> Hello.</i> 
We do owe you an apology.

321
00:13:45,784 --> 00:13:48,827
We shouldn't have said
those things about you.

322
00:13:54,041 --> 00:13:55,376
I guess the lesson here

323
00:13:55,376 --> 00:13:58,879
is that I sometimes use guilt
as a weapon.

324
00:13:58,879 --> 00:14:00,131
What are you doing?

325
00:14:00,131 --> 00:14:02,634
Oh, just shooting
a talking head.

326
00:14:02,634 --> 00:14:05,178
Or did you want me to be
the only one

327
00:14:05,178 --> 00:14:07,555
who didn't have one?

328
00:14:07,555 --> 00:14:09,474
No, go ahead.

329
00:14:10,517 --> 00:14:12,477
I think it stems
from when I was--

330
00:14:16,773 --> 00:14:18,191
So you found my father?

331
00:14:18,191 --> 00:14:20,151
Yes, he's on his way.

332
00:14:20,151 --> 00:14:22,612
I mean,
if this is too much to handle,

333
00:14:22,612 --> 00:14:25,281
I completely understand,
and I can call it off.

334
00:14:25,281 --> 00:14:27,867
Actually,
I think I'm ready to see him.

335
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:29,786
Good. Good for you.

336
00:14:31,954 --> 00:14:33,873
Oh.
I should probably tell you.

337
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:36,751
If you're lying to me,
if my father isn't coming,

338
00:14:36,751 --> 00:14:39,838
if a car pulls up and anyone
other than my father steps out,

339
00:14:39,838 --> 00:14:41,798
say, an actor,
or you in a wig,

340
00:14:41,798 --> 00:14:44,676
if you pull any<i> Ferris Bueller,</i>
<i>Parent Trap, Three's Company,</i>

341
00:14:44,676 --> 00:14:48,012
<i>F/X, F/X2: The Deadly Art</i>
<i>of Illusion</i> ********,

342
00:14:48,012 --> 00:14:49,556
I will beat you.

343
00:14:49,556 --> 00:14:53,560
And there will be nothing
madcap or wacky about it.

344
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:56,688
Understood?
Crystal.

345
00:15:09,701 --> 00:15:10,951
Hi.
Hey.

346
00:15:10,951 --> 00:15:12,912
I'm LeVar.
Oh, I know.

347
00:15:12,912 --> 00:15:14,455
I was a huge fan of<i> Rebop.</i>

348
00:15:14,455 --> 00:15:16,165
It was canceled
before I was born,

349
00:15:16,165 --> 00:15:18,793
but I scored
some VHS copies.

350
00:15:18,793 --> 00:15:21,337
I was nostalgic
from a very early age.

351
00:15:21,337 --> 00:15:23,005
Cool.

352
00:15:23,005 --> 00:15:25,508
Hey, you know, I assumed
that Troy was a fan,

353
00:15:25,508 --> 00:15:27,510
but he hasn't said a word
since I got here.

354
00:15:27,510 --> 00:15:29,512
And now I've gotta catch
this flight--

355
00:15:29,512 --> 00:15:31,013
No, no, you can't go.

356
00:15:31,013 --> 00:15:33,767
He loves you. He talks
about you all the time.

357
00:15:33,767 --> 00:15:35,101
How much would it cost

358
00:15:35,101 --> 00:15:37,228
to change your flight
till tomorrow?

359
00:15:37,228 --> 00:15:40,607
Is $261 enough?
Because that's all I've got.

360
00:15:40,607 --> 00:15:43,276
That's all you've got?
Yeah.

361
00:15:43,276 --> 00:15:48,030
No, you keep your money.
I'll reschedule.

362
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:51,701
Oh, my God, Thank you.
He's gonna be so happy.

363
00:15:51,701 --> 00:15:53,953
You know,
you are a very generous friend.

364
00:15:53,953 --> 00:15:56,289
But you're really stupid
with your money.

365
00:15:59,250 --> 00:16:01,335
It's not that I'm selfish,
it's just that

366
00:16:01,335 --> 00:16:03,880
I'm really stupid
with my money.

367
00:16:03,880 --> 00:16:05,882
Which is why
I'll never have a lot of it.

368
00:16:05,882 --> 00:16:08,718
And because
I'm a really generous friend.

369
00:16:08,718 --> 00:16:11,345
Problem solved,
dilemma deleted.

370
00:16:11,345 --> 00:16:13,765
Britta for the win.

371
00:16:14,808 --> 00:16:16,976
Oh. Thank God
he didn't take it.

372
00:16:16,976 --> 00:16:20,688
Could you imagine bouncing
a check to Kunta Kinte?

373
00:16:39,206 --> 00:16:41,751
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

374
00:16:45,379 --> 00:16:46,631
Hello?

375
00:16:46,631 --> 00:16:50,259
MAN:
<i>Jeffrey? This is your father.</i>

376
00:16:50,259 --> 00:16:51,511
Uh-huh.

377
00:16:51,511 --> 00:16:53,847
<i>It's me,</i>
<i>here in this sedan.</i>

378
00:16:53,847 --> 00:16:56,599
<i>See? I'm waving.</i>

379
00:16:56,599 --> 00:16:59,393
<i>I'm sorry I can't come</i>
<i>any closer, my boy.</i>

380
00:16:59,393 --> 00:17:01,896
<i>This is too difficult.</i>

381
00:17:01,896 --> 00:17:04,106
<i>You look too much</i>
<i>like your mother.</i>

382
00:17:04,106 --> 00:17:06,609
<i>No, don't come closer.</i>
<i>As you were.</i>

383
00:17:06,609 --> 00:17:08,569
<i>I have to catch a flight</i>
<i>to Katmandu,</i>

384
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:10,070
<i>but I just wanted to say,</i>

385
00:17:10,070 --> 00:17:12,866
<i>cherish the new friends</i>
<i>that you've made.</i>

386
00:17:12,866 --> 00:17:15,994
They're your true family
now.

387
00:17:15,994 --> 00:17:17,704
[TIRES SCREECHING]

388
00:17:17,704 --> 00:17:21,040
No, don't open-- It'll be
too hard on both of us. Aah!

389
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:23,584
JEFF: Son of a--
PIERCE: Jeffrey, I'm dying.

390
00:17:23,584 --> 00:17:25,211
JEFF:
Quiet.

391
00:17:25,211 --> 00:17:27,213
TROY: Jeff!
BRITTA: No, no, no.

392
00:17:27,213 --> 00:17:29,423
PIERCE:
<i>When you improvise a plan,</i>

393
00:17:29,423 --> 00:17:31,217
sometimes you hit
a speed bump,

394
00:17:31,217 --> 00:17:34,303
and sometimes you hit it
so hard,

395
00:17:34,303 --> 00:17:36,597
that you soar
through the air,

396
00:17:36,597 --> 00:17:39,099
far beyond
your initial expectations.

397
00:17:39,099 --> 00:17:41,978
<i>I set out to take revenge</i>
<i>on Jeff Winger,</i>

398
00:17:41,978 --> 00:17:44,522
<i>to scare him</i>
<i>with the ghost of his father.</i>

399
00:17:44,522 --> 00:17:48,401
<i>Instead, I took over the role</i>
<i>of his father.</i>

400
00:17:48,401 --> 00:17:50,945
<i>Helped make him</i>
<i>a better man.</i>

401
00:17:50,945 --> 00:17:52,321
It'll be a long time

402
00:17:52,321 --> 00:17:55,282
before Jeff Winger
underestimates me again.

403
00:17:55,282 --> 00:17:57,577
Ha-ha-ha-- Ow, ow, ow!

404
00:17:58,953 --> 00:18:00,788
Why would you
do something like this?

405
00:18:00,788 --> 00:18:03,082
TROY: Come on, Jeff.
JEFF: What?

406
00:18:04,751 --> 00:18:08,588
Because I'm sick of you people
not taking me seriously.

407
00:18:08,588 --> 00:18:10,464
You forget my birthday.

408
00:18:10,464 --> 00:18:13,801
You don't invite me to your
Dungeons &amp; Dragons games

409
00:18:13,801 --> 00:18:16,012
or your secret trampoline.

410
00:18:16,012 --> 00:18:19,139
You guys think
I'm some kind of a joke.

411
00:18:19,139 --> 00:18:21,601
This isn't disproving
the theory.

412
00:18:22,936 --> 00:18:25,187
Good point.
What'd you say?

413
00:18:25,187 --> 00:18:27,147
TROY: No, Jeff.
What did you say?

414
00:18:27,147 --> 00:18:30,902
JEFF:
<i>Apparently, I need to say</i>
<i>some things to my father.</i>

415
00:18:30,902 --> 00:18:35,322
<i>Things that I may have</i>
<i>screamed at Pierce instead.</i>

416
00:18:35,322 --> 00:18:38,826
I'm not saying
he doesn't deserve it,

417
00:18:38,826 --> 00:18:41,579
but my father deserves it
too.

418
00:18:42,663 --> 00:18:44,331
Pierce?

419
00:18:45,583 --> 00:18:46,960
I figured out your test.

420
00:18:46,960 --> 00:18:51,589
Crowns, presents,
punishments, favorites.

421
00:18:51,589 --> 00:18:54,550
You're trying to show me
the dangers of my own elitism.

422
00:18:54,550 --> 00:18:57,386
My constant striving
to be the best.

423
00:18:57,386 --> 00:19:00,974
So I'm re-queathing
this tiara.

424
00:19:01,933 --> 00:19:03,350
If I become the person

425
00:19:03,350 --> 00:19:05,645
who thinks it's their place
to pick favorites

426
00:19:05,645 --> 00:19:09,523
and torture the rest,
I'll die sad and alone.

427
00:19:09,523 --> 00:19:12,944
And that's what you were trying
to teach me.

428
00:19:12,944 --> 00:19:17,281
Very good, Annie. You pass.

429
00:19:20,242 --> 00:19:22,495
[DOOR OPENS THEN CLOSES]

430
00:19:22,495 --> 00:19:24,872
She's actually
just my favorite.

431
00:19:24,872 --> 00:19:27,207
[♪♪♪]

432
00:19:28,709 --> 00:19:30,795
ABED:
<i>I thought</i>
<i>the documentary format</i>

433
00:19:30,795 --> 00:19:32,505
<i>would be like</i>
<i>fish in a barrel.</i>

434
00:19:32,505 --> 00:19:34,674
<i>But as is the case</i>
<i>with a real barrel of fish,</i>

435
00:19:34,674 --> 00:19:38,511
<i>after a while it can become</i>
<i>cramped, chaotic and stinky.</i>

436
00:19:38,511 --> 00:19:39,929
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

437
00:19:39,929 --> 00:19:42,181
ABED:
<i>Fortunately,</i>
<i>if your documentary</i>

438
00:19:42,181 --> 00:19:44,183
<i>is turning out</i>
<i>just as messy as real life,</i>

439
00:19:44,183 --> 00:19:46,060
<i>wrap it up</i>
<i>with random shots</i>

440
00:19:46,060 --> 00:19:49,063
<i>which, when cut together</i>
<i>under a generic voice-over,</i>

441
00:19:49,063 --> 00:19:52,608
<i>suggest a profound</i>
<i>thematic connection.</i>

442
00:19:52,608 --> 00:19:56,195
I'm not knocking it.
It works.

443
00:19:56,195 --> 00:19:57,864
Guys.

444
00:20:03,036 --> 00:20:04,787
BRITTA:
Oh.

445
00:20:04,787 --> 00:20:07,373
ANNIE &amp; SHIRLEY:
Aww.

446
00:20:08,791 --> 00:20:14,213
Jeff and I became kind of like
father and son today.

447
00:20:14,213 --> 00:20:16,674
JEFF:
No, we did not.

448
00:20:19,886 --> 00:20:23,347
Troy, I am telling you, man,
this salmon is really good.

449
00:20:24,473 --> 00:20:26,100
[SIGHS]

450
00:20:26,100 --> 00:20:28,769
Would you mind
passing me the pepper?

451
00:20:29,937 --> 00:20:31,856
[SIGHS]

452
00:20:34,108 --> 00:20:37,945
♪ Butterfly in the sky ♪

453
00:20:39,446 --> 00:20:42,241
♪ I can go twice as high ♪

454
00:20:42,241 --> 00:20:45,661
♪ Take a look
It's in a book ♪

455
00:20:45,661 --> 00:20:46,829
[WHIMPERS]

456
00:20:46,829 --> 00:20:48,831
♪ The<i> Reading Rainbow</i> ♪

457
00:20:48,831 --> 00:20:53,002
[SCREAMING AND SOBBING]

458
00:20:55,046 --> 00:20:59,633
Oh, well.
More fish for Kunta.
